<p>
<seg id=1> At the same time, in the area of Chinatown in Jakarta, the capital of Indonesia, ethnic Chinese and local Indonesians stand shoulder to shoulder protecting their homes. </seg>
<seg id=2> After severe rioting and disturbances broke out in May, Chinatown was again hit by violence. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to another report filed by Voice of America reporter Grant from Jakarta. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The curtain of night is about to fall and soldiers fire their guns in warning to disperse young people in the Chinatown area who are throwing rocks at them. </seg>
<seg id=5> Several hours earlier, a crowd of several thousand set fire to a bank less than one kilometer away from the Presidential Palace, and the fierce fire quickly approached nearby stores. </seg>
<seg id=6> A band of young people used a streetlamp post to break open the door of a shop. </seg>
<seg id=7> When the ethnic Chinese were attacked on Saturday, a crowd of people pulled a Chinese out onto the street and beat him, and then threw him into a ditch. </seg>
<seg id=8> Later, the military brought in an armored personnel carrier and saved this severely injured person. </seg>
<seg id=9> Tanks patrol streets full of rocks and broken glass, thousands of soldiers carrying guns and tear-gas grenades protect the local commercial district, keeping thugs away. </seg>
<seg id=10> Merchants dealing in electrical appliance products there were forced to move away from their shops following the violence in May. </seg>
<seg id=11> This reporter saw a 29-year-old youth whose last name was Min wearing just shorts and a belt on guard behind a barricade equipped with wire entanglement. </seg>
<seg id=12> This youth who works at a computer company says he and a Muslim neighbor will stand guard there all night to prevent thugs from entering their homes and robbing them. </seg>
<seg id=13> Mr. Min says his neighbors erected this wire entanglement after the violence in May, but did not think they would need it so soon. </seg>
<seg id=14> In such places with roadblocks, residents carry big wooden sticks and drive off stranger after stranger. </seg>
<seg id=15> A resident called Daxiyate wears a Muslim cap on his head a Muslim sarong on his body. </seg>
<seg id=16> He tells this reporter that most of the plundering young people heard that a riot had occurred here and came in from outside of Chinatown. </seg>
<seg id=17> Thugs looted and demolished a subway station a block away, and the road is covered with shoes, computers, and clothing hangers discarded during pursuit by soldiers. </seg>
</p>
